      ‚Äñ We avoid this terminology because it conflicts with sets. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â
    ) of $a$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ \ssubsection{Notation} ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Since the natural numbers are ordered, we regularly denote
    finite sequences from left to right between parentheses. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ For example, we denote $a: \set{1, ‚Ä¶, 4} ‚Üí A$ by $(a_1,
    a_2, a_3, a_4)$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $a(k)$ is the $k$th term. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Following the convention with functions, we regularly usually
    denote $a(n)$ by $a_n$ ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ \ssubsection{Orderings and numberings} ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Let $A$ be a set with $\num{A} = n$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ A sequence $a: \set{1, ‚Ä¶, n} ‚Üí A$ is an ‚ù¨ordering‚ù≠ of $A$
    if $a$ is invertible. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ In this case, we call the inverse a ‚ù¨numbering‚ù≠ of $A$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ An ordering associates with each number a unique object and
    a numbering associates with each object a unique number (the
    object‚Äôs ‚ù¨index‚ù≠). ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ \ssubsection{Relation to Direct Products} ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨natural direct product‚ù≠ is a product of a sequence of
    sets. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We denote the direct product of a sequence of sets $A_1,
    ‚Ä¶, A_n$ by $‚àè_{i = 1}^{n} A_i$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If each $A_i$ is the same set $A$, then we denote the
    product $‚àè_{i = 1}^{n} A_i$ by $A^n$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The set of sequences in a set $A$ is the direct product
    $A^n$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ \ssection{Natural unions and intersections} ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We denote the family union of the finite sequence of sets
    $A_1$, $\dots$, $A_n$ by $\union_{i = 1}^{n} A_i$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Similarly, we denote the intersection by $\intersection_{i =
    1}^{n} A_i$ ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ \ssection{Slices} ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ An ‚ù¨index range‚ù≠ for a list $s$ of length $n$ is a pair
    $(i, j)$ for which $1 \leq i < j \leq n$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The ‚ù¨slice‚ù≠ corresponding to the index range $(i,j)$ is the
    length $j-i$ sequence $s'$ defined by $s'_1 = s_{i}$, $s'_2
    = s_{i+1}, \dots, s'_{j} = s_{i + j-1}$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We denote the $(i,j)$-slice of $s$ by $s_{i:j}$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If $i = 1$ we use $s_{:j}$ and if $j = n$ we use
    $s_{i:}$ as shorthands for the slices $s_{1:j}$ and $s{i:n}$. ‚¶â
